, <i>Reynaud</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Raginald</i>, from <i>ragin</i> ‘counsel, decision’ + <i>wald</i> ‘rule, ruler’), first introduced to England by Scandinavian settlers in the Old Norse form <i>Rögnvaldr</i> (see   Ronald  ) and greatly reinforced after the Conquest by the Norman forms <i>Reinald</i> and <i>Reynaud</i>, which often appear Latinized as <i>Reginaldus</i>. The surname was later much confused with   Raynor   and   Renard  . The surname is occasionally also borne by Jews, in which case it presumably represents an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Reynell V was born in 1243, in Pitney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, his father, Walter Reynell IV, was 27 and his mother, Jane Maria, was 23. He married Maud de Trumpington in 1279, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in November 1327, in Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 84."},"et":{"1243–November 1327":"1243–november 1327","1243–1327":"1243–1327","1249–1320":"1249–1320","1254–1280":"1254–1280","1280–1364":"1280–1364","1216–1272":"1216–1272","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1280":"1280","1327":"1327","November 1327":"november 1327","1216":"1216","1249